<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What HTML elements does this converter handle?", answer: "The converter supports h1-h6 headings, p paragraphs, strong/b for bold, em/i for italic, del/s for strikethrough, a links, img images, ul/ol/li lists, blockquote, pre/code for code blocks, hr horizontal rules, and table/thead/tbody/tr/th/td for tables. Unsupported or unknown elements have their text content extracted." },
  { question: "What happens to HTML attributes and styles?", answer: "Attributes like class, id, and style are dropped since Markdown has no concept of styling. The converter preserves only the structural and semantic meaning of the HTML: href attributes on links, src and alt on images, and language classes on code elements." },
  { question: "Can I convert an entire web page?", answer: "You can paste the HTML of any page section. For best results, paste the content area rather than the full page source, since navigation menus, scripts, and meta tags do not have Markdown equivalents. The converter extracts text from any elements it encounters, so even full-page HTML produces output, but the result is cleanest with content-focused HTML." },
  { question: "Is any data sent to a server?", answer: "No. The conversion uses the DOMParser API built into your browser to parse the HTML, then walks the parsed tree to generate Markdown. Everything runs locally in JavaScript with no network requests." },
  { question: "How are nested elements handled?", answer: "The converter processes elements recursively. A bold word inside a heading, a link inside a list item, or an image inside a paragraph all produce the expected nested Markdown syntax. Deeply nested structures are supported as long as each element maps to a Markdown construct." }
]) %>

